e=\"background:#fcc;\" |[[Golden State Warriors]]<br />([[2016 NBA Playoffs#Conference Finals: (1) Golden State Warriors vs. (3) Oklahoma City Thunder|Lost 3\u20134]])\n| \n|\n|-\n| [[2016\u201317 Oklahoma City Thunder season|2016\u201317]]\n| 47\u201335\n| 6th\n| style=\"background:#fcc;\" |Houston Rockets<br />([[2017 NBA Playoffs#(3) Houston Rockets vs. (6) Oklahoma City Thunder|Lost 1\u20134]])\n| \n| \n| \n|\n|-\n| [[2017\u201318 Oklahoma City Thunder season|2017\u201318]]\n| 48\u201334\n| 4th\n| style=\"background:#fcc;\" |[[Utah Jazz]]<br />([[2018 NBA Playoffs#(4) Oklahoma City Thunder vs. (5) Utah Jazz|Lost 2\u20134]])\n| \n| \n| \n|\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Oklahoma City Thunder season|2018\u201319]]\n| 49\u201333\n| 6th\n| style=\"background:#fcc;\" |[[Portland Trail Blazers]]<br />([[2019 NBA Playoffs#(3) Portland Trail Blazers vs. (6) Oklahoma City Thunder|Lost 1\u20134]])\n| \n| \n| \n|\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 NBA season|2019\u201320]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| colspan=\"12\" style=\"{{NBA color cell2|Oklahoma City Thunder}};text-align:left;\"|\u2020 Denotes Division championship\n|}\n\n==Home arenas==\n<!-- Do not remove arenas from Seattle. The Oklahoma City team is keeping the franchise history of the SuperSonics. Please see the talk page for link to settlement. -->\n''Note: All arenas used before 2008 were used by the defunct Seattle SuperSonics franchise.''\n\nSeattle arenas had hosted two [[NBA All-Star Game]]s; the [[1974 NBA All-Star Game|1974]] game in [[Seattle Center Coliseum]] and the [[1987 NBA All-Star Game|1987]] game in the [[Kingdome]], where SuperSonics forward [[Tom Chambers (basketball)|Tom Chambers]] grabbed [[NBA All-Star Game Most Valuable Player Award|MVP]] honors.\n*'''[[Seattle Center Coliseum]]''' 1967\u20131978 (occasionally used during the Kingdome years when the latter was unavailable due to either [[Seattle Mariners|Mariners]] or [[Seattle Seahawks|Seahawks]] games)\n*'''[[Kingdome]]''' 1978\u20131985\n*'''Seattle Center Coliseum''' 1985\u20131994\n*'''[[Tacoma Dome]]''' 1994\u20131995 (During Seattle Center Coliseum renovation)\n*'''[[KeyArena]]''' (the remodeled and renamed Seattle Center Coliseum) 1995\u20132008\n\n===Chesapeake Energy Arena (2008\u2013present)===\n{{main|Chesapeake Energy Arena}}\nOpened on June 8, 2002, as the Ford Center, Chesapeake Energy Arena was built without luxury accommodations but designed to accommodate luxury \"buildouts\" should a professional sports franchise make the Chesapeake Energy Arena their home arena. It was finished at a cost of $89.2 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chesapeakearena.com/about-the-arena/overview|title=Overview {{!}} Chesapeake Energy Arena|last=Arena|first=Chesapeake Energy|website=www.chesapeakearena.com|access-date=December 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nA plan for such build-out improvements began in 2007. It came in the wake of the acquisition of the Seattle SuperSonics by [[Professional Basketball Club LLC|an Oklahoma City-based ownership group]] the previous October. A city ballot initiative approved by a 62 percent margin on March 4, 2008, extended a prior one-cent city sales tax for a period of 15 months in order to fund $101 million in budgeted improvements to the arena and a separate $20 million practice facility for a relocated franchise.<ref name=knapp1>{{cite web |url=http://okc.about.com/od/politicalparties/a/fordcentervote.htm |title=Ford Center Arena Improvement Plan |last=Knapp |first=Adam |accessdate=November 17, 2010 |publisher=[[About.com]]}}</ref>\n\nRenovation work on the arena was delayed by a sales tax-receipts shortfall during the 2008\u201310 economic crisis.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.okc.gov/agendapub/cache/2/xo5hufii3c1njdqg3sqfuw55/98900111172010122518933.PDF |title=MAPS 3 Citizens Advisory Board Presentation |date=August 24, 2010 |work=City of Oklahoma City |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160411001503/http://www.okc.gov/agendapub/cache/2/xo5hufii3c1njdqg3sqfuw55/98900111172010122518933.PDF |archivedate=April 11, 2016 }}</ref> Revised plans limited the size of a new glass entryway and eliminated a practice court to accommodate the shortfall.<ref>{{cite web |last=Rohde |first=John |title=Ford Center practice gym eliminated from renovations |url=http://www.newsok.com/article/3483508 |work=The Oklahoman |date=August 8, 2010 |accessdate=November 17, 2010}}</ref> Major construction work on the arena expansion was also delayed from the summer of 2010 to the summer of 2011. Seating capacity of the stadium is 18,203 for professional NBA basketball games.\n\nSimilar revisions were made to the plans for the Thunder's separate practice facility, for a total cost savings of approximately $14 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newsok.com/article/3474044 |title=Oklahoma City might save as much as $14 million on Ford Center renovations, practice facility |work=The Oklahoman |date=July 7, 2010 |accessdate=November 17, 2010}}</ref> The Thunder's practice facility completion date was pushed back to approximately March 2011.<ref>{{cite web |last=Rohde |first=John |title=Thunder practice facility set for March completion |url=http://newsok.com/thunder-practice-facility-set-for-march-completion/article/3515264 |work=The Oklahoman|date=November 16, 2010 |accessdate=November 17, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Mascots==\n<!-- Do not remove mascots from Seattle. Please see the talk page for link to settlement. -->\n''Note: All mascots used before 2008 were used by the defunct Seattle SuperSonics franchise.''\n*[[Wheedle]], 1978\u20131985\n*[[Squatch]], 1993\u20132008\n\n===Rumble the Bison===\n{{main|Rumble the Bison}}\nOn February 17, 2009, Rumble the Bison was introduced as the new Oklahoma City Thunder mascot during halftime of a game against the [[2008\u201309 New Orleans Hornets season|New Orleans Hornets]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Rumble the Bison Debuts as Thunder Mascot|url=http://www.nba.com/thunder/news/rumbledebuts_090217.html|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=February 17, 2009|accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref> Rumble was the winner of the 2008\u20132009 NBA Mascot of the Year.<ref name=\"award\">{{cite press release|title=Rumble the Bison Named NBA Mascot of the Year|url=http://www.nba.com/thunder/news/release_090813.html|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=August 13, 2009|accessdate=August 26, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Fanbase==\nDuring the [[2012 NBA Finals]], sportswriter [[Bill Simmons]] published a piece on the team's fan base in his [[ESPN]]-sponsored Web outlet, ''[[Grantland|Grantland.com]]'', in which he noted the unusual enthusiasm of the city for its team:\n{{cquote|With the possible exception of [[Portland Trail Blazers|Portland]], no NBA team means more to its city. This goes beyond having the loudest fans. There's genuine devotion here. These people arrived a good 45 minutes early for last night's Game 1&nbsp;\u2014 and by \"these people\" I mean \"everyone with a ticket\"&nbsp;\u2014 then clapped their way through pregame warm-ups with such infectious enthusiasm that I remember saying to a friend, \"No way these yahoos keep this up for three hours, they're going to burn out.\" Wrong. You know what burned out? My eardrums. My head is still ringing.<ref name=Simmons>{{cite web|last=Simmons|first=Bill|authorlink=Bill Simmons|title=Thunder Family Values|url=http://www.grantland.com/story/_/id/8047976/thunder-family-values|work=[[Grantland|Grantland.com]]|date=June 13, 2012|accessdate=June 4, 2013}}</ref>}}\n\nSimmons speculated that the [[Oklahoma City bombing]] played a major part in the team's culture, noting that Thunder general manager [[Sam Presti]] has every new Thunder player visit the [[Oklahoma City National Memorial]], and encourages players to look into the stands and consider that many of the team's fans were personally affected by the event. He also noted, however, that the fact that the Thunder is the only team from Oklahoma City (or indeed the state of Oklahoma) in one of the nation's four major leagues contributes mightily to the city's devotion.<ref name=Simmons/>\n\nThunder fans are also reportedly much more likely to attend major home games than most other NBA fanbases. According to a source in the ticket industry, only five percent of tickets to the 2012 NBA conference finals listed for sale on secondary market sites such as [[StubHub]] were for Thunder home games, and for every ticket listed for a Thunder home game in the 2012 NBA Finals, 10 tickets for Heat home games were listed.<ref name=Simmons/>\n\nThe team and its fanbase regularly use the slogan \"Thunder Up!\" which was prominently displayed on T-shirts during the 2012 playoffs.\n\n==Players==\n===Current roster===\n{{Oklahoma City Thunder roster}}\n<!-- Do not place the depth chart in this article, since it constitutes point of view and original research -->\n\n===Former players===\n:''For the complete list of players see: [[Seattle SuperSonics all-time roster]] / [[Oklahoma City Thunder all-time roster]]''\n\n===Retained draft rights===\nThe Thunder holds the draft rights to the following unsigned draft picks who have been playing outside the NBA. A drafted player, either an international draftee or a college draftee who is not signed by the team that drafted him, is allowed to sign with any non-NBA teams. In this case, the team retains the player's draft rights in the NBA until one year after the player's contract with the non-NBA team ends.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbafaq.com/salarycap.htm|title=NBA Salary Cap FAQ \u2013 2011 Collective Bargaining Agreement|quote=If the player is already under contract to, or signs a contract with a non-NBA team, the team retains the player's draft rights for one year after the player's obligation to the non-NBA team ends. Essentially, the clock stops as long as the player plays pro ball outside the NBA.|first=Larry|last=Coon|authorlink=Larry Coon|accessdate=April 13, 2014}}</ref> This list includes draft rights that were acquired from trades with other teams.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:left; font-size:90%;\"\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell|Oklahoma City Thunder}};\"|Draft\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell|Oklahoma City Thunder}};\"|Round\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell|Oklahoma City Thunder}};\"|Pick\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell|Oklahoma City Thunder}};\"|Player\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell|Oklahoma City Thunder}};\"|Pos.\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell|Oklahoma City Thunder}};\"|Nationality\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell|Oklahoma City Thunder}};\"|Current team\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell|Oklahoma City Thunder}};\"|Note(s)\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"{{NBA color cell|Oklahoma City Thunder}};\"|Ref\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[2003 NBA draft|2003]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|34\n| {{sortname|Sofoklis|Schortsanitis}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|C\n| {{flagu|Greece}}\n| [[Ionikos Nikaias B.C.|Ionikos Nikaias]] ([[Greek Basket League|Greece]])\n| Acquired from the [[Los Angeles Clippers]] (via [[Atlanta Hawks|Atlanta]])\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite news|title=Thunder Acquires Schortsanitis and Trade Exception|url=http://www.nba.com/thunder/release_schortsanitis_140715|date=July 15, 2014|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|accessdate=February 4, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[2003 NBA draft|2003]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|35\n| {{sortname|Szymon|Szewczyk}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| F/C\n| {{flagu|Poland}} \n| [[KK W\u0142oc\u0142awek|Anwil W\u0142oc\u0142awek]] ([[Polish Basketball League|Poland]])\n| Acquired from the [[Milwaukee Bucks]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite news|title=Thunder Acquires Trade Exception|url=http://www.nba.com/thunder/news/release_tradeexception_130711|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=July 11, 2013|accessdate=April 21, 2014}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===