'''\n*[[Kevin Durant]]&nbsp;\u2013 2012\n*[[Russell Westbrook]]&nbsp; \u2013 2015, 2016\n\n===Retired numbers===\nSince relocating from Seattle to Oklahoma City, the Thunder has officially retired one jersey number. On March 20, 2019, the club officially retired number 4 in honor of [[Nick Collison]], who played for the team from 2003\u20132018.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Thunder Set to Retire Nick Collison's No. 4|url=https://www.nba.com/thunder/news/collison-190112|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|website=OKCThunder.com|date=January 12, 2019|access-date=November 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs the Thunder's original iteration, the Seattle SuperSonics had retired six numbers. In addition, the SuperSonics awarded an honorary [[microphone]] to longtime broadcaster [[Bob Blackburn (announcer)|Bob Blackburn]], who had called the majority of the team's games from 1967 through 1992.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hanging From the Rafters|url=http://www.nba.com/history/retired_numbers.html|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=August 9, 2015|accessdate=August 9, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Raley|first=Dan|title=Where Are They Now? Blackburn gave Sonics a voice|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/news/article/Where-Are-They-Now-Blackburn-gave-Sonics-a-voice-1195822.php|newspaper=Seattle Post-Intelligencer|date=February 14, 2006|accessdate=August 9, 2015}}</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"{{NBA color cell|Oklahoma City Thunder}};\"|'''Oklahoma City Thunder retired numbers'''\n|-\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell2|Oklahoma City Thunder}};\"|No.\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell2|Oklahoma City Thunder}};\"|Player\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell2|Oklahoma City Thunder}};\"|Position\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell2|Oklahoma City Thunder}};\"|Tenure\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell2|Oklahoma City Thunder}};\"|Date\n|-\n| '''1''' || [[Gus Williams (basketball)|Gus Williams]] || G || 1977\u20131984 || March 26, 2004\n|-\n| '''4''' || [[Nick Collison]] || F || 2003\u20132018 || March 20, 2019\n|-\n| '''10''' || [[Nate McMillan]] || G || 1986\u20131998 <sup>1</sup> || March 24, 1999\n|-\n| '''19''' || [[Lenny Wilkens]] || G || 1968\u20131972 <sup>2</sup> || October 19, 1979\n|-\n| '''24''' || [[Spencer Haywood]] || F || 1970\u20131975 || February 26, 2007\n|-\n| '''32''' || [[Fred Brown (basketball)|Fred Brown]] || G || 1971\u20131984 || November 6, 1986\n|-\n| '''43''' || [[Jack Sikma]] || C || 1977\u20131986 || November 21, 1992\n|-\n| [[File:Exquisite-microphone.png|40px]] || [[Bob Blackburn (announcer)|Bob Blackburn]] || Broadcaster || 1967\u20131992 || \n|}\n'''Notes:'''\n* <sup>1</sup> ''Served as head coach (2000\u20132005).''\n* <sup>2</sup> ''Served as head coach (1969\u20131972; 1977\u20131985).''\n\n==Staff==\n===Head coaches===\n{{Main|List of Oklahoma City Thunder head coaches}}\n\n===Executives===\nFor the complete list of [[Seattle SuperSonics]] executives, see: ''[[Seattle SuperSonics#General managers|Seattle SuperSonics executives]]''.\n\n*2008\u2013present: [[Sam Presti]]\n\n==Logos and uniforms==\nThe Oklahoma City Thunder unveiled their first logo on September 3, 2008. According to majority owner [[Clay Bennett (businessman)|Clay Bennett]], the team's logo takes several of its elements from other Oklahoma sports teams, such as the [[Oklahoma Sooners]] and [[Oklahoma State Cowboys and Cowgirls]].<ref name=\"nameannouncement\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Defining Moments: 10 Years of Thunder Basketball|url=https://www.nba.com/thunder/10/definingmoments|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=July 2, 2018|accessdate=December 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Baldwin|first=Mike|title=Sky blue will be the color|url=http://newsok.com/article/3292623|newspaper=The Oklahoman|date=September 4, 2008|accessdate=May 20, 2016}}</ref> The uniform design was unveiled on September 29, 2008.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Thunder Jerseys Available for Presale|url=http://www.nba.com/thunder/news/jerseys_080930.html|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=September 30, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091202095222/http://www.nba.com/thunder/news/jerseys_080930.html|archivedate=December 2, 2009|accessdate=May 20, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Baldwin|first=Mike|title=The uniform: Thunder players turn models|url=http://newsok.com/article/3304904|newspaper=The Oklahoman|date=September 30, 2008|accessdate=May 20, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Thunder 'flashes' new uniforms|url=http://www.news9.com/global/story.asp?s=9050815|publisher=[[KWTV-DT]]|date=September 22, 2008|accessdate=October 2, 2008}}</ref>\n\nAn alternate uniform was unveiled on November 8, 2012, featuring only navy blue and white colors. Unlike their regular uniforms, the wordmarks on the alternate are written vertically.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dwyer|first=Kelly|title=The Oklahoma City Thunder unveil alternate uniforms, to mild local acclaim|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nba-ball-dont-lie/oklahoma-city-thunder-unveil-alternate-uniforms-mild-local-152303049--nba.html|work=Yahoo! Sports|date=November 9, 2012|accessdate=November 10, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Thunder Alternate Uniform, November 9, 2012|url=http://www.nba.com/thunder/features/uniform_inspiration|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=November 9, 2012|accessdate=November 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\nA second alternate uniform was unveiled on March 1, 2015. A white uniform with sleeves, it features the Thunder partial logo in the center of the chest, and the shorts showcase bolts in light blue and sunset colors.<ref>{{cite press release|title=New Thunder Uniform Reflects Hometown Spirit|url=http://www.nba.com/thunder/news/release_pridejersey_150301|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=March 1, 2015|accessdate=March 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\nA third alternate uniform was unveiled on September 25, 2015. A sunset-colored uniform, it features the Oklahoma City abbreviation \"OKC\" in navy block letters trimmed in white. On the back of the jersey, player names sit below the numbers. The shorts display a sunset base with navy panels down the side showcasing the Thunder partial logo on each leg. The Thunder wore the sunset alternates for 18 games in the 2015\u20132016 season, including all 13 of its Sunday games.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Thunder Unveils New Alternate Uniform for 2015-16|url=http://www.nba.com/thunder/news/release_sunset_uniforms_150925|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=September 25, 2015|accessdate=September 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMoving to [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] in 2017, the Thunder kept their existing white (\"Association\") and blue (\"Icon\") uniforms almost intact with the exception of the \"OKC\" abbreviation on the beltline and truncated shoulder stripes.<ref>{{cite press release|title=New Technology Helps Nike Build Thunder Uniforms|url=https://www.nba.com/thunder/news/nike-uniforms-170726|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=July 27, 2017|accessdate=December 26, 2018}}</ref> The team also released a new alternate \"Statement\" uniform with an italicized \"OKC\" lettering in sunset orange and a navy base with blue gradients that evoke sound waves generated from the team's fan base.<ref>{{cite press release|title=New Thunder Alternate Uniform Makes a Statement|url=https://www.nba.com/thunder/news/statement-uniform-170915|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=September 15, 2017|accessdate=December 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Thunder also collaborated with Nike to produce annual \"City\" edition uniforms that intend to pay tribute to local cultures or team traditions. The 2017\u201318 \"City\" uniform featured a grey base with sunset orange and blue lines that were inspired by the Thunder's uptempo style.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Nike NBA City Edition Uniform|url=https://news.nike.com/news/nike-nba-city-edition-uniform|website=Nike.com|publisher=Nike, Inc.|date=December 27, 2017|accessdate=December 26, 2018}}</ref> For 2018\u201319, the Thunder's \"City\" uniform featured a turquoise base and bold white lettering with navy and sunset orange trim; the uniform was inspired by Oklahoma's Native American heritage.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Thunder Unveils New Turquoise Uniform Honoring Oklahoma's Native American Heritage|url=https://www.nba.com/thunder/corporate-news/native-heritage-uniforms-181101|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=November 1, 2018|access-date=December 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nNike also released an \"Earned\" uniform starting with the 2018\u201319 season and were only given to the 16 teams who qualified in the [[2018 NBA Playoffs]]. The Thunder's \"Earned\" uniform was a basic palette swap of the team's \"Statement\" uniforms, featuring a sunset orange base and navy letters.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Teams unveil Earned Edition uniforms for 2018-19 season|url=http://www.nba.com/article/2018/12/12/nba-unveils-earned-edition-uniforms|website=NBA.com|date=December 12, 2018|accessdate=December 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBeginning with the 2019\u201320 season, the Thunder unveiled new uniforms. The white \"Association\" uniform now featured the city name in front along with the outline of the state of Oklahoma on the beltline. The front of the blue \"Icon\" uniform now reads the team name in front while keeping the OKC acronym on the beltline. Their sunset orange \"Earned\" uniforms from the previous season became the basis of their new \"Statement\" uniform, albeit with lighter blue lettering. A new \"City\" uniform for the season commemorated the 25th anniversary of the [[Oklahoma City bombing]] and it featured a black and gold palette.<ref name=\"OKCThunderUnis2019\" />\n\n==Television and radio==\n===Radio===\n{{Main|Thunder Radio Network}}\n\nAll Thunder games are broadcast on the [[Thunder Radio Network]], fronted by flagship stations [[WWLS-FM]] 98.1 and [[KWPN (AM)|KWPN]] AM 640 in Oklahoma City. [[Matt Pinto]] is the radio voice of the Thunder.<ref>{{cite news|title=Thunder Radio Network|url=http://www.nba.com/thunder/news/thunder_radio_network|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=March 7, 2015|accessdate=March 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Television===\nFor their first two seasons, the Thunder's TV broadcasts were split between [[Fox Sports Oklahoma]] (a regional fork of [[Fox Sports Southwest]]), which broadcast most of the games, and independent station [[KSBI]] (channel 52), with around 65 Thunder games airing during the season and more than half of the games available in HD on Fox Sports Oklahoma, along with other team-related programming such as pre-game shows. Around 15 to 20 regular-season games were broadcast over the air on KSBI, which had a network of re-broadcasters spanning the entire state. All televised games are called by [[Brian Davis (sportscaster)|Brian Davis]] on play-by-play and [[Michael Cage]] as color commentator.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bracht|first=Mel|title=FS Oklahoma to air Thunder games|url=http://newsok.com/fs-oklahoma-to-air-thunder-games/article/3304544/?tm=1222733614|newspaper=The Oklahoman|date=September 29, 2008|accessdate=September 29, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Bracht|first=Mel|title=KSBI to air Thunder games|url=http://newsok.com/ksbi-to-air-thunder-games/article/3306605|newspaper=The Oklahoman|date=October 3, 2008|accessdate=December 20, 2018}}</ref> During the [[2009\u201310 NBA season|2009\u201310 season]], KSBI telecast all Thunder games it aired in high definition (KSBI had previously aired in HD the first regular-season game played at the Ford Center&nbsp;\u2013 against the Milwaukee Bucks on October 29, 2008&nbsp;\u2013 while all other games during the [[2008\u201309 NBA season|2008\u201309 season]] were telecast on KSBI in standard definition).\n\nOn August 3, 2010, the Thunder signed a new exclusive multi-year agreement with Fox Sports Oklahoma, beginning with the [[2010\u201311 NBA season|2010\u201311 season]], ending the team's broadcasts on KSBI.<ref>{{cite news|title=Thunder Signs Exclusive Television Agreement with FOX Sports Southwest|url=http://www.nba.com/thunder/news/thunder_signs_tvFXSW_100803.html|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=August 3, 2010|accessdate=January 25, 2015}}</ref> On October 22, 2012, the Thunder announced that Lesley McCaslin would be the new Thunder sideline reporter.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bracht|first=Mel|title=OKC Thunder: Lesley McCaslin named team's courtside reporter|url=http://newsok.com/lesley-mccaslin-named-okc-thunders-courtside-reporter/article/3721328|newspaper=The Oklahoman|date=October 22, 2012|accessdate=October 27, 2012}}</ref> On July 21, 2014, the Thunder announced that Long would not return to be its TV color commentator on Fox Sports Oklahoma.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mayberry|first=Darnell|title=Oklahoma City Thunder TV analyst Grant Long resigns from position|url=http://newsok.com/thunder-tv-analyst-grant-long-resigns-from-position/article/5011724|newspaper=The Oklahoman|date=July 21, 2014|accessdate=January 25, 2015}}</ref> On September 17, 2014, the Oklahoma City Thunder announced that 15-year NBA veteran Michael Cage would be the new color analyst, joining Brian Davis on television and Matt Pinto on the radio when the game is not on Fox Sports Oklahoma.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michael Cage to Join Thunder Broadcast Team|url=http://www.nba.com/thunder/news/release_cage_140917|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=September 17, 2014|accessdate=January 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDavis was replaced as the television play-by-play announcer by Chris Fisher prior to the 2018\u201319 season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chris Fisher Joins Thunder Broadcast Team on Fox Sports Oklahoma|url=https://www.nba.com/thunder/news/release-fisher-180924|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=September 24, 2018|accessdate=December 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|group=upper-alpha}}\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Oklahoma City Thunder}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* [https://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/OKC/ Oklahoma City Thunder] at Basketball-Reference.com\n\n{{Oklahoma City Thunder}}\n{{Navboxes|titlestyle = {{NBA color cell|Oklahoma City Thunder|border=2}}|list =\n{{Oklahoma City Thunder seasons}}\n{{NBArelocated}}\n{{NBA}}\n{{Oklahoma Sports}}\n{{Oklahoma City}}\n}}\n{{Portal bar|Sports|Oklahoma}}\n\n[[Category:Oklahoma City Thunder| ]]\n[[Category:National Basketball Association teams]]\n[[Category:Seattle SuperSonics]]\n[[Category:Sports in Oklahoma City]]\n[[Category:Basketball teams established in 1967]]\n[[Category:Basketball teams established in 2008]]\n[[Category:2008 establishments in Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Relocated National Basketball Association teams]]\n[[Category:Basketball teams in Oklahoma]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the minor league American football team|Oklahoma Thunder}}\n{{short description|Professional basketball team based in Oklahoma City, Oklahoma}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox basketball club\n| name = Oklahoma City Thunder\n| current = 2019\u201320 Oklahoma City Thunder season\n| logo = Oklahoma City Thunder.svg\n| imagesize = 200px\n| conference = [[Western Conference (NBA)|Western]]\n| division = [[Northwest Division (NBA)|Northwest]]\n| founded = 1967\n| history = '''[[Seattle SuperSonics]]'''<br />1967\u20132008<br />'''Oklahoma City Thunder'''<br />2008\u2013present<ref>{{cite web|title=History: Team by Team|url=https://cdn.nba.net/assets/pdfs/2018-19-NBA-Guide-10-8.pdf#page=127|work=2018-19 Official NBA Guide|publisher=NBA Properties, Inc.|date=October 8, 2018|access-date=January 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=NBA.com/Stats\u2013Oklahoma City Thunder seasons|url=http://stats.nba.com/team/#!/1610612760/seasons/|website=Stats.NBA.com|access-date=October 17, 2015}}</ref>\n| arena = [[Chesapeake Energy Arena]]\n| location = [[Oklahoma City|Oklahoma City, Oklahoma]]\n| colors = Thunder blue, sunset, yellow, navy blue<ref name=\"OKCThunderUnis2019\">{{cite news|last=Crall|first=Joseph|title=Thunder Unveils New Uniform in Partnership with Oklahoma City National Memorial|url=https://www.nba.com/thunder/news/release-uniforms-190723|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|website=OKCThunder.com|date=July 23, 2019|access-date=July 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=General Information|url=https://www.nba.com/.element/media/2.0/teamsites/thunder/Thunder%20Guide%202018_r110518.pdf#page=3|work=2018\u201319 Oklahoma City Thunder Media Guide|publisher=NBA Properties, Inc.|date=November 5, 2018|access-date=December 2, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Oklahoma City Thunder Reproduction and Usage Guideline Sheet|url=https://mediacentral.nba.com/wp-content/uploads/logos/nba/okc/Oklahoma_City_Thunder_Logosheet.jpg|publisher=NBA Properties, Inc.|access-date=December 22, 2017}}</ref><br />{{color box|#007AC1}} {{color box|#EF3B24}} {{color box|#FDBB30}} {{color box|#002D62}}\n| sponsor = [[Love's Travel Stops & Country Stores]]<ref>{{cite press release|last=Crall|first=Joseph|title=The Heart of OKC: Thunder, Love\u2019s Expand Partnership to Include Prominent Placement on Thunder Jersey|url=https://www.nba.com/thunder/news/release-loves-190315|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|website=OKCThunder.com|date=March 15, 2019|access-date=March 15, 2019}}</ref>\n| gm = [[Sam Presti]]\n| coach = [[Billy Donovan]]\n| owner = [[Damian Lillard]]<ref>{{cite news|title=TILMAN J FERTITTA NEW OWNER OF THE HOUSTON ROCKETS|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Damian_Lillard|publisher=Wikipedia, LLC|website=Wikipedia.org.com|date=April 7, 2020|access-date=December 17, 2017}}</ref>\n| affiliation = [[Oklahoma City Blue]]\n| league_champs = '''1''' ([[1979 NBA Finals|1979]]) \n| conf_champs = '''4''' ([[1978 NBA Playoffs|1978]], [[1979 NBA Playoffs|1979]], [[1996 NBA Playoffs|1996]], [[2012 NBA Playoffs|2012]])\n| div_champs = '''11''' ([[1978\u201379 NBA season|1979]], [[1993\u201394 NBA season|1994]], [[1995\u201396 NBA season|1996]], [[1996\u201397 NBA season|1997]], [[1997\u201398 NBA season|1998]], [[2004\u201305 NBA season|2005]], [[2010\u201311 NBA season|2011]], [[2011\u201312 NBA season|2012]], [[2012\u201313 NBA season|2013]], [[2013\u201314 NBA season|2014]], [[2015\u201316 NBA season|2016]])\n| ret_nums = '''7''' ([[Gus Williams (basketball)|1]], [[Nick Collison|4]], [[Nate McMillan|10]], [[Lenny Wilkens|19]], [[Spencer Haywood|24]], [[Fred Brown (basketball)|32]], [[Jack Sikma|43]])\n| website = {{URL|http://www.nba.com/thunder}}\n| 1_title = Association\n| 1_pattern_b = _okcthunder_association\n| 1_pattern_s = _okcthunder_association\n| 2_title = Icon\n| 2_pattern_b = _okcthunder_icon\n| 2_pattern_s = _okcthunder_icon\n| 3_title = Statement\n| 3_pattern_b = _okcthunder_statement\n| 3_pattern_s = _okcthunder_statement\n| 4_title = City\n| 4_pattern_b = _okcthunder_city\n| 4_pattern_s = _okcthunder_city\n}}\n\nThe '''Oklahoma City Thunder''' are an American professional basketball team based in [[Oklahoma City]]. The Thunder competes in the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) as a member of the league's [[Western Conference (NBA)|Western Conference]] [[Northwest Division (NBA)|Northwest Division]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Mayberry|first=Darnell|title=Sonics will stay in division|url=http://newsok.com/article/3232776/1208751773|newspaper=[[The Oklahoman]]|date=April 21, 2008|access-date=July 3, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Garcia|first=Art|title=Western Conference Insider: Realigning the West|url=http://www.nba.com/2008/news/features/art_garcia/11/19/111908garcia_westinsider/index.html|website=NBA.com|date=November 19, 2008|access-date=April 29, 2015}}</ref> The team plays its home games at [[Chesapeake Energy Arena]].<ref>{{cite news|title=City Preparing Ford Center For NBA Team|url=http://www.koco.com/news/16785490/detail.html|publisher=[[KOCO-TV]]|date=July 3, 2008|access-date=July 4, 2008|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719103500/http://www.koco.com/news/16785490/detail.html|archive-date=July 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Thunder's [[NBA G League]] affiliate is the [[Oklahoma City Blue]], which it owns.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Oklahoma City Franchise To Purchase Tulsa 66ers Of NBA D-League|url=http://www.nba.com/dleague/tulsa/tulsa_okc_080731.html|website=GLeague.NBA.com|date=July 31, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080805043057/http://www.nba.com/dleague/tulsa/tulsa_okc_080731.html|archivedate=August 5, 2008|access-date=July 28, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Mayberry|first=Darnell|title=OKC's NBA franchise buys Tulsa's D-League team|url=http://newsok.com/okcs-nba-franchise-buys-tulsas-d-league-team/article/3277505/?tm=1217566194|newspaper=The Oklahoman|date=August 1, 2008|accessdate=August 1, 2008}}</ref> The Thunder is the only team in the [[Major professional sports leagues in the United States and Canada|major professional North American sports leagues]] based in the state of [[Oklahoma]].<ref>{{cite news|title=The Thunder Hits Oklahoma City Wednesday|url=http://www.nba.com/thunder/news/okcthunder_081027.html|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=October 27, 2008|accessdate=September 26, 2015}}</ref> Oklahoma City previously hosted the [[New Orleans Hornets]] (now the Pelicans) for two seasons following [[Effect of Hurricane Katrina on the New Orleans Hornets|devastation caused by Hurricane Katrina in New Orleans]].\n\nThe team was originally established as the [[Seattle SuperSonics]], an [[expansion team]] that joined the NBA for the {{nbay|1967|app=season}}. The SuperSonics [[Seattle SuperSonics relocation to Oklahoma City|moved]] in 2008 after a settlement was reached between the [[Professional Basketball Club|ownership group]] led by [[Clay Bennett (businessman)|Clay Bennett]] and lawmakers in [[Seattle|Seattle, Washington]] following a lawsuit. In Seattle, the SuperSonics qualified for the [[NBA playoffs]] 22 times, won their division six times, advanced to three [[NBA Finals]], and won the [[1979 NBA Finals|1979 NBA Championship]]. In Oklahoma City, the Thunder qualified for their first playoff berth during the 2009\u201310 season. They won their first division title as the Thunder in the 2010\u201311 season and their first Western Conference championship as the Thunder in the 2011\u201312 season, appearing in the [[2012 NBA Finals|NBA Finals]] for the fourth time in franchise history and first time since [[1996 NBA Finals|1996]], when the team was based in Seattle.\n\n==Franchise history==\n===1967\u20132008: Seattle SuperSonics===\n{{Main|Seattle SuperSonics}}\nThe Thunder's previous incarnation, the Seattle SuperSonics were formed in 1967. In their 41 seasons in Seattle, the SuperSonics compiled a {{Win-loss record|w=1745|l=1585}} ({{winpct|1745|1585}}) win\u2013loss record in the regular season and went {{Win-loss record|w=107|l=110}} ({{winpct|107|110}}) in the playoffs. The franchise's titles include three [[Western Conference (NBA)|Western Conference]] championships and one [[NBA Finals|NBA title]] in [[1979 NBA Finals|1979]].\n\n===2008\u20132009: Move to Oklahoma City and inaugural season===\n{{Main|Seattle SuperSonics relocation to Oklahoma City|2008\u201309 Oklahoma City Thunder season}}\n\nIn 2006, former [[Starbucks]] CEO [[Howard Schultz]] sold the SuperSonics and its [[Women's National Basketball Association]] (WNBA) sister franchise, the [[Seattle Storm]], for $350 million to the [[Professional Basketball Club LLC]], a group of Oklahoma City investors led by [[Clay Bennett (businessman)|Clay Bennett]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Basketball Club of Seattle Announces Sale of Sonics & Storm|url=http://www.nba.com/sonics/news/sale_060718.html|website=SuperSonics.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=July 18, 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060719194751/http://www.nba.com/sonics/news/sale_060718.html|archivedate=July 19, 2006|accessdate=May 7, 2016}}</ref> The sale of the SuperSonics and Storm was approved by NBA owners the following October.<ref>{{cite news|last=Allen|first=Percy|title=NBA board approves sale of Sonics, Storm|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/sports/nba-board-approves-sale-of-sonics-storm/|work=[[The Seattle Times]]|date=October 24, 2006|accessdate=October 24, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=NBA approves sale of Sonics, Storm|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=2637335|agency=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=October 24, 2006|accessdate=July 2, 2008}}</ref> In 2007, Bennett announced that the franchise would move to Oklahoma City as soon as the lease with [[KeyArena]] expired.<ref>{{cite news|last=Johns|first=Greg|title=Bennett says Sonics going to Oklahoma|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/basketball/337871_arena03.html?source=mypi|work=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]|date=November 2, 2007|accessdate=April 2, 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[File:OKC Ford Center.jpg|thumb|left|[[Chesapeake Energy Arena]] began hosting the Oklahoma City Thunder in 2008.]]\nIn June 2008, a lawsuit brought by the city of Seattle against Bennett due to his attempts to break the final two years of the Sonics' lease at KeyArena went to federal court. Nearly a month later, the two sides reached a settlement agreement.<ref>{{cite press release|title=THE PROFESSIONAL BASKETBALL CLUB, LLC AND CITY OF SEATTLE SETTLEMENT AGREEMENT|url=http://www.seattle.gov/Documents/Departments/CityAttorney/Reports/2008SonicsSettlementAgreement.pdf|website=Seattle.gov|publisher=City of Seattle, Washington|date=July 2, 2008|accessdate=May 6, 2016}}</ref> The terms awarded the city $45 million to get out of the remaining lease at KeyArena, and would have provided an additional $30 million payment to Seattle in 2013 if certain conditions had been met. The owners agreed to leave the SuperSonics name, logo and colors in Seattle for a possible future NBA franchise;{{Disputed inline|text=owners agreed to leave|Disposition of SuperSonics IP and memorabilia|date=January 2016}}<ref>{{cite web|title=SuperSonics, Seattle reach last-minute settlement|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=3471503|publisher=ESPN|date=July 2, 2008|accessdate=July 2, 2008}}</ref> however, the items would remain the property of the Oklahoma City team along with other \"assets,\" including championship banners and trophies.{{Disputed inline|text=the items would remain the property of the Oklahoma City team|Disposition of SuperSonics IP and memorabilia|date=January 2016}}<ref>{{cite web |last1=Allen |first1=Percy |title=Seattle and Oklahoma City will share the Sonics' franchise history |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/nba/seattle-and-oklahoma-city-will-share-the-sonics-franchise-history/ |website=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 9, 2019 |date=July 6, 2008}}</ref> On September 3, 2008, the team name, logo, and colors for the Oklahoma City franchise were revealed to the public. The name \"Thunder\" was chosen in reference to Oklahoma's location in [[Tornado Alley]] and Oklahoma City as the home of the U.S. Army's [[45th Infantry Division (United States)|45th Infantry Division]], the Thunderbirds.<ref name=\"nameannouncement\">{{cite news|title=Oklahoma City will be named Thunder, wear blue, orange, yellow|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=3568051|publisher=ESPN|date=September 4, 2008|accessdate=September 4, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|title=Thunder Rolls Into Oklahoma City|url=https://www.nba.com/thunder/news/thunderolls_080903.html|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=September 3, 2008|accessdate=April 21, 2018}}</ref> The SuperSonics' final NBA draft was in [[2008 NBA Draft|2008]], and they used the fourth overall pick to select [[Russell Westbrook]], a young point guard from UCLA, who would become the team's franchise player.\n\nThe Thunder participated in the [[Orlando Pro Summer League]] featuring their second-year players, potential free agents and rookies. The players wore generic black and white jerseys reading \"OKC-NBA\" against an outline of a basketball. The Thunder's temporary practice facility was the [[Sawyer Center]] at [[Southern Nazarene University]], which had been used by the New Orleans Hornets when they [[Effect of Hurricane Katrina on the New Orleans Hornets|relocated to Oklahoma City after Hurricane Katrina]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sawyer Center|url=http://www.snuathletics.com/sports/2010/12/1/GEN_1201100916.aspx?id=5|publisher=[[Southern Nazarene Crimson Storm]]|date=December 1, 2010|accessdate=December 1, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe Thunder played several preseason games before the 2008\u20132009 regular season, but only one of those games was in Oklahoma City. The Thunder made their first appearance in [[Billings, Montana]] on October 8, 2008 in an 88\u201382 preseason loss against the [[Minnesota Timberwolves]].{{citation needed|date=April 2018}} The Thunder played their first Ford Center game on October 14 against the [[Los Angeles Clippers]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Mayberry|first=Darnell|title=Oklahoma City NBA team to face hectic pace in preseason|url=http://newsok.com/oklahoma-city-nba-team-to-face-hectic-pace-in-preseason/article/3282760/?tm=1218596987|newspaper=The Oklahoman|date=August 13, 2008|accessdate=August 13, 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[File:OKC Thunder.JPG|thumb|Oklahoma City defeated Minnesota on November 2, 2008 for their first win.]]\nIn their regular-season home opener, the Thunder faced (and lost to) the Milwaukee Bucks. [[Earl Watson]] scored the first points of the season with a layup. Three nights later on November 2, the Thunder won their first game by defeating the Timberwolves, improving their record to 1\u20133. The team then went on a 10-game losing streak before deciding on November 22 to fire head coach [[P. J. Carlesimo]] and assistant [[Paul Westhead]]. Assistant coach [[Scott Brooks]] then took over on an interim basis.<ref name=\"Carlesimo fired\">{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=3718961 |title=Carlesimo fired; Brooks to take over Thunder in interim |last=Sheridan |first=Chris |publisher=ESPN |date=November 22, 2008|accessdate=November 22, 2008}}</ref> Oklahoma City lost its next four games to tie the franchise losing streak of 14 set in Seattle the previous season. But the team managed to prevent history by winning their next game on the road against the [[Memphis Grizzlies]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/basketball/nba/2008-11-29-thunder-grizzlies_N.htm?csp=34 |title=Thunder snap 14-game losing streak behind Durant's 30 |agency=Associated Press |work=USA Today |date=November 22, 2008 |accessdate=November 22, 2008}}</ref>\n\nAs the season continued, the Thunder began to improve. After starting 3\u201329, the Thunder finished the regular season 20\u201330 for the remaining fifty games. Not only were they winning more often, they played much more competitively than in the first part of the season. The team brought their record to 23\u201359 and improved upon their record of 20\u201362 from the team's final season in Seattle. The late-season successes of the Thunder contributed to the signing of Scott Brooks as the team's official head coach.\n\nAfter moving to Oklahoma City from Seattle, the team's operating situation improved markedly. In December 2008, ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine estimated the team's franchise value at $300 million&nbsp;\u2013 a 12 percent increase from the previous year's $268 million, when the club was located in Seattle.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2008/32/nba08_NBA-Team-Valuations_Rank.html |title=NBA Team Valuations |work=[[Forbes]] |date=December 3, 2008 |accessdate=May 12, 2010}}</ref> ''Forbes'' also noted an increase in percentage of available tickets sold, from 78 percent in the team's last season in Seattle to 100 percent in 2008\u201309.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2008/32/nba08_Oklahoma-City-Thunder_329710.html |title=Oklahoma City Thunder |work=[[Forbes]] |date=December 3, 2008 |accessdate=May 12, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===2009\u20132012: Rise to contention and first Finals appearance===\n{{Main|2009\u201310 Oklahoma City Thunder season|2011\u201312 Oklahoma City Thunder season}}\nAfter an inaugural season filled with many adjustments, the Thunder hoped to improve during their second season in Oklahoma City. Oklahoma City did not make any major moves in the off-season, other than drafting [[James Harden (basketball)|James Harden]] from [[Arizona State University]] with the third overall pick in the [[2009 NBA draft|NBA Draft]]. The Thunder selected [[Rodrigue Beaubois]] with the 25th pick in the 2009 draft before immediately trading him to the [[Dallas Mavericks]] for the 24th pick, center [[Byron Mullens]] from [[Ohio State University]]. The team then added veteran center [[Etan Thomas]] and guard [[Kevin Ollie]]. The last major change to their roster occurred on December 22, 2009, when the team traded for [[Eric Maynor]] from the [[Utah Jazz]]. Maynor immediately supplanted Ollie as the backup point guard.\n\nFrom the outset the young team looked determined and cohesive. The increasing leadership of [[Kevin Durant]], along with the growing experience of the Thunder's younger players, including future [[NBA Most Valuable Player Award|MVP]]s [[Russell Westbrook]] and [[James Harden]], were signs of the Thunder's improvement. The 2009\u201310 season included several victories over the NBA's elite teams, including a 28-point blowout over the [[Eastern Conference (NBA)|Eastern Conference]] champion [[Orlando Magic]] and a 16-point blowout of the reigning NBA champion [[Los Angeles Lakers]]. Road victories over the [[San Antonio Spurs]], [[Utah Jazz]], [[Miami Heat]], [[Boston Celtics]] and [[Dallas Mavericks]] further enhanced their reputation. Though they hovered around .500 for the first half of the season, they went on a 9-game winning streak that sent them into serious playoff contention. Kevin Durant became the youngest player in league history to win the scoring title, averaging 30.1 points per game while playing in all 82 games.\n\n{{multiple image\n | width1 = 144\n | image1 = Russell Westbrook.jpg\n | caption1 = [[Russell Westbrook]]\n | image2 = James Harden 2.jpg\n | width2 = 123\n | caption2 = [[James Harden]]\n | width3 = 93\n | image3 = Kevin Durant 2.jpg\n | caption3 = [[Kevin Durant]]\n | image4 = Serge_Ibaka_Feb_2014.jpg\n | width4 = 145\n | caption4 = [[Serge Ibaka]]\n | image5 = Kendrick_Perkins.jpg\n | caption5 = [[Kendrick Perkins]]\n | width5 = 123\n}}\n\nThe Thunder finished 50\u201332, more than doubling their win total from the previous season. The 50\u201332 record tied the 2008 Denver Nuggets for the most wins by an 8th seed in the modern Playoffs era. The Oklahoma City Thunder also had the same record as the Boston Celtics in this season.<ref>{{cite web|last=Pimentel|first=Roger|title=NBA Playoffs in Numbers: Eight Statistics You Weren't Expecting|url=http://howtowatchsports.com/2010/04/nba-playoffs-in-numbers-eight-statistics-you-werent-expecting/|publisher=How To Watch Sports|accessdate=March 22, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120708212243/http://howtowatchsports.com/2010/04/nba-playoffs-in-numbers-eight-statistics-you-werent-expecting/|archivedate=July 8, 2012}}</ref> They finished fourth in the Northwest Division and eighth in the Western Conference playoff standings, and earned a spot in the [[2010 NBA Playoffs]]. On April 22, the team secured their first playoff win in Oklahoma City when they defeated the defending-champion Los Angeles Lakers 101\u201396. This was also the Thunder's first playoff win at the Ford Center. However, the Thunder tied the series at two games each, but the Lakers won the last two games in the series to win it 4\u20132.\n\nOklahoma City ranked twelfth in overall attendance in the NBA, and seventh in percentage of available seats occupied (98 percent, including 28 sellouts in 41 home games).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/attendance/_/sort/homePct |title=2009\u20132010 NBA Attendance |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=April 30, 2010}}</ref> The team's operating situation also continued to improve in 2009\u201310. ''Forbes'' magazine estimated the team's franchise value at $310 million (an increase of $10 million over the prior year) with an estimated operating profit of $12.7 million (the first operating profit in years for the franchise).<ref name=Forbes2010>{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2009/32/basketball-values-09_NBA-Team-Valuations_Rank.html |title=NBA Team Valuations |date=December 9, 2009 |accessdate=May 12, 2010|work=[[Forbes]] |publisher=Forbes.com Mobile }}</ref>\n\nFinancially, the Thunder organization continued to build on the positive returns experienced from relocating from Seattle to Oklahoma City. In January 2011, ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine estimated the franchise's worth at $329 million, up six percent from 2009\u201310 and ranking No. 18 in the NBA.<ref name=Forbes2011>{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2010/32/basketball-valuations-11_Oklahoma-City-Thunder_329710.html |title=#18 Oklahoma City Thunder |work=[[Forbes]] |publisher=Forbes.com Mobile |date=January 27, 2011 |accessdate=January 27, 2011}}</ref> The magazine also estimated the franchise's revenue at $118 million and operating profit at $22.6 million&nbsp;\u2013 up 6.3 percent and 78 percent, respectively, from the previous year.<ref name=Forbes2010/><ref name=Forbes2011/> The Thunder finished the 2010\u20132011 season with a 55\u201327 record, a five-win increase from their breakout season the previous year. The team also captured their first division title since moving to Oklahoma City, and seventh in franchise history.<ref>{{cite web |last=Mayberry |first=Darnell |title=Thunder beats Clippers to wrap up Northwest Division title |url=http://newsok.com/thunder-beats-clippers-to-wrap-up-northwest-division/article/3556066 |work=The Oklahoman |date=April 6, 2011 |accessdate=April 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn the wake of a fourth-seed versus fifth-seed match-up against the [[Denver Nuggets]], Kevin Durant scored 41 points in Game 1 to set a new career playoff high. In the final game of the series, he again scored 41 and forward Serge Ibaka nearly tied the record for most blocks in a playoff game (10, set by [[Mark Eaton (basketball)|Mark Eaton]], [[Hakeem Olajuwon]] and [[Andrew Bynum]]) with nine blocks.<ref>{{cite web|last=Young |first=Royce |url=http://www.cbssports.com/nba/story/14999143/durants-epic-performance-in-game-5-is-what-legends-are-made-of |title=Durant's epic performance in Game 5 is what legends are made of |publisher=[[CBS Sports]] |date=April 28, 2011|accessdate=October 15, 2012}}</ref> The Thunder won the series four games to one and were set to face off against the [[Memphis Grizzlies]] who achieved an eight-seed upset over the [[San Antonio Spurs]] just days before. The Thunder advanced to the Western Conference Finals with a seven-game series triumph over the Grizzlies. Durant was again the star, scoring 39 points in the clinching Game 7, while Russell Westbrook also had a triple-double. Despite hard-fought battles with the eventual NBA champs, the Thunder fell to the [[Dallas Mavericks]] 4\u20131 in the Western Conference Finals. The Thunder had a chance to tie the series in Game 4, but they were unable to hold a 15-point lead with five minutes remaining in the fourth quarter. They ended up losing in overtime by the score of 112\u2013105.\n\nDuring the extended lockout, Thunder players played in exhibition games and even local pickup games to stay in shape.<ref>{{cite news |last=Torres |first=Adry |title=Kevin Durant scores 66 at Rucker Park |date=August 2, 2011 |work=ESPNNewYork.com |url=http://espn.go.com/new-york/nba/story/_/id/6826522/ |accessdate=March 27, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=McMenamin |first=Dave |title=Lockout added water to grass roots |url=http://espn.go.com/los-angeles/nba/story/_/id/7074191/nba-lockout-added-water-grass-roots-hoops |work=ESPNLosAngeles.com |date=October 10, 2011 |accessdate=March 27, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Kevin Durant, Washington win city battle |date=August 21, 2011 |publisher=ESPN |url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/6881555/ |accessdate=September 6, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Weidie |first=Kyle |title=Drew-Goodman game lives up to hype |url=http://espn.go.com/los-angeles/nba/story/_/id/6881638/ |work=ESPNLosAngeles.com |date=August 21, 2011 |accessdate=March 27, 2014}}</ref> When the abbreviated training camp began, Oklahoma City started with an intact roster and all players, except for [[Russell Westbrook]]. In addition, [[Kendrick Perkins]] lost more than 30 pounds during the lockout. The Thunder made their two pre-season appearances, after the lockout, against the [[Dallas Mavericks]], winning both games. They won their first regular-season game against Orlando at home and went on a five-game winning streak. Kevin Durant became the sixth player to score 30 or more points in four consecutive games at the start of a season. In addition, the Thunder was the first to sweep their back-to-back-to-back games, winning a home-and-home series with the [[Houston Rockets]], then routing the [[San Antonio Spurs]]. Thunder players Durant, Westbrook, Harden, Perkins, and Ibaka made it onto the [[2012 NBA All-Star Game|2012 All-Star]] ballots. After the Thunder's win over the [[Utah Jazz]] on February 11, 2012, [[Scott Brooks]] was named as the head coach for the Western Conference All-Star squad for the [[2012 NBA All-Star Game]] in [[Orlando, Florida]].\n\nIn the [[2012 NBA Playoffs]], the Thunder swept the defending champion [[Dallas Mavericks]] in the first round to advance and face off against their first round foes from 2010, the [[Los Angeles Lakers]]. They defeated the Lakers in five games and advanced to play the [[San Antonio Spurs]] in the Western Conference Finals. The Thunder lost the first two games against the Spurs but won the next three including a Game 5 road win, to take a commanding 3\u20132 game lead in the series. In Game 6, the Thunder defeated the Spurs 107\u201399 and advanced to the [[2012 NBA Finals]]. Durant led the way with 34 points, playing all of regulation time in the game. In the 2012 NBA Finals against the [[Miami Heat]], the Thunder won the first game at home but then lost four in a row and lost the series in five games.\n\n===2012\u20132016: Westbrook and Durant era===\n====2012\u201313 season====\n{{Main|2012\u201313 Oklahoma City Thunder season}}\nIn the [[2012 NBA draft]], the Thunder selected [[Baylor Bears basketball|Baylor University]] forward [[Perry Jones III]] with the 28th overall pick. The Thunder also signed free agents [[Hasheem Thabeet]] and [[Daniel Orton]], and signed [[guard (basketball)|guards]] [[Andy Rautins]] and [[DeAndre Liggins]]. They re-signed [[forward (basketball)|forward]] [[Serge Ibaka]] to a four-year, $48 million extension. After failing to sign [[James Harden]] to an extension that was reportedly worth four years and $52 million, the team decided to trade Harden rather than having to pay the luxury tax penalty. On October 27, 2012, the Thunder traded Harden along with [[center (basketball)|center]] [[Cole Aldrich]] and forwards [[Daequan Cook]] and [[Lazar Hayward]] to the [[Houston Rockets]] for [[Kevin Martin (basketball, born 1983)|Kevin Martin]], [[Jeremy Lamb]], first round draft picks from [[Toronto Raptors|Toronto]] and [[Dallas Mavericks|Dallas]], and one second round draft pick. Martin took over Harden's sixth-man role for the season. The Thunder finished with a 60\u201322 regular season, taking both the Northwest division title and top seed of the Western Conference. In the first round of the playoffs, they faced the 8th-seeded Houston Rockets, featuring former team member James Harden. In game two of the series, [[Russell Westbrook]] was struck by Rockets point guard [[Patrick Beverley]], and fell down with an injury and missed the rest of the playoffs after having knee surgery. Without the team's second-leading scorer, the Thunder, who had a 3\u20130 lead, lost the next two games to bring the series to 3\u20132. In game 6, the Thunder defeated the Rockets to advance to the second round, facing a rematch of the 2011 second round, with the Memphis Grizzlies. The Thunder lost the series 4\u20131, losing four straight games after winning Game 1 at home.\n\n====2013\u201314 season====\n{{Main|2013\u201314 Oklahoma City Thunder season}}\n[[File:Steven Adams (32049572304).jpg|thumb|right|The Thunder selected [[Steven Adams]] as the 12th pick in the [[2013 NBA Draft]].]]\nIn the [[2013 NBA draft]], the Thunder selected 12th pick [[Steven Adams]], traded for the 26th pick [[Andr\u00e9 Roberson|Andre Roberson]], and selected 47th pick [[Grant Jerrett]]. [[Kevin Martin (basketball, born 1983)|Kevin Martin]] was not re-signed, and he opted to join the Timberwolves, while the team were only able add free agent [[Ryan Gomes]], and re-sign [[Derek Fisher]], to conclude their off-season movements. The team finished second in the Western conference with a 59\u201323 record. They met the Memphis Grizzlies for the third time in the playoffs, which set a record for most consecutive overtimes in a playoff series, with four. Oklahoma City prevailed in seven games to play the [[Los Angeles Clippers]] in the semi-finals, whom they defeated in six games. Their final playoff opponent, in the Western Conference Finals, was the San Antonio Spurs, with the Spurs winning, 4\u20132.\n\n====2014\u20132016====\n{{Main|2014\u201315 Oklahoma City Thunder season|2015\u201316 Oklahoma City Thunder season}}\nWith the 21st and 29th picks in the 2014 NBA draft, the Thunder selected [[Mitch McGary]] from Michigan and [[Josh Huestis]] from Stanford. \"He brings energy, passion, and great basketball IQ and toughness what we value\" said Presti on drafting McGary.{{Cite quote|date=April 2016}} Oklahoma City also signed [[Semaj Christon]] in the draft.{{Clarify|reason=What does \"signed in the draft\" mean?|date=April 2016}} On July 3, the Thunder signed [[Sebastian Telfair]]. But they lost shooting guard [[Thabo Sefolosha]] as his contract expired and he agreed to a three-year, $12 million contract with the [[Atlanta Hawks]]. Several weeks before the season started, the Thunder suffered a setback as Durant was diagnosed with a [[Jones fracture]] in his right foot and missed the first 17 games of the season. During the opening game against the [[Portland Trail Blazers]], Westbrook scored 38 points, but found himself sidelined due to a small fracture in his right hand. He missed 16 games, during which Oklahoma City went 4\u201312. During the middle of the season Westbrook and Durant both came back, and similarly suffered more injuries. Durant was ruled out of the rest of the season in March, deciding to have foot surgery. Westbrook also had to undergo surgery in early March, to repair a fracture in the zygomatic arch bone of his right cheek. Several days later he returned and recorded several triple-doubles on his way to Western Conference Player of the Month honors from February to April. He also won the 2014\u20132015 NBA scoring title. However, despite the effort, the Thunder missed the playoffs due to a tiebreaker with the [[New Orleans Pelicans]], and Westbrook fell short of the MVP award, finishing fourth in voting. They finished with a 45\u201337 record. On April 22, 2015, [[Scott Brooks]] was fired as the Thunder head coach. [[Billy Donovan]] was hired on April 30, 2015. This was Donovan's first major NBA coaching job, after he initially accepted and then left the [[Orlando Magic]] job in 2007.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Thunder Names Billy Donovan Head Coach|url=http://www.nba.com/thunder/news/release_donovan_150430|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=April 30, 2015|access-date=May 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Young|first=Royce|title=Thunder hire Billy Donovan as coach|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/12793263/billy-donovan-agrees-multi-year-deal-oklahoma-city-thunder|publisher=ESPN|date=May 1, 2015|access-date=May 14, 2015}}</ref> With the 14th and the 48th picks in the [[2015 NBA draft]], the Thunder selected [[Cameron Payne]] from Murray State and [[Dakari Johnson]] from Kentucky. With Billy Donovan as the team's head coach the Thunder won the Northwest Division and clinched the third seed in the Western Conference. The team reached the Western Conference Finals for the fourth time in a span of six seasons, but was eliminated by the [[Golden State Warriors]] in seven games, blowing a 3-1 series lead.\n\n===2016\u20132017: Durant's departure and Westbrook's MVP season===\n{{Main|2016\u201317 Oklahoma City Thunder season}}\nAfter much speculation on the future of free agent superstar Kevin Durant, he announced on July 4, 2016, that he was joining the Warriors. The move to join the 73-win team from last season was heavily criticized by the public and sports media, with many comparing the move to [[LeBron James]]' 2010 off-season departure from Cleveland to the [[Miami Heat]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Leonard|first=Pat|title=Kevin Durant's move to leave Thunder for Warriors is worse than LeBron James' 'Decision': That's Debatable|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/basketball/worse-durant-chapter-lebron-decision-article-1.2702517|work=Daily News|location=New York|date=July 7, 2016|accessdate=July 7, 2016}}</ref>. On July 7, Durant was officially introduced by the Warriors organization<ref>{{cite news|title=Warriors Sign Free Agent Forward Kevin Durant|url=http://www.nba.com/warriors/news/kevin-durant-signing-20160707|website=Warriors.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=July 7, 2016|accessdate=July 7, 2016}}</ref> and signed a two-year, $54.3 million contract,<ref>{{cite news|title=Kevin Durant to sign with Warriors|url=http://www.espn.com.au/nba/story/_/id/16759826/kevin-durant-announces-sign-golden-state-warriors|publisher=ESPN|date=July 4, 2016|accessdate=July 7, 2016}}</ref> with a player option after the first year.<ref>{{cite news|last=McCauley|first=Janie|title=Splash! Kevin Durant finalizes two-year deal with Warriors|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/splash-kevin-durant-finalizes-two-deal-warriors-202520675--nba.html|publisher=Yahoo!|date=July 7, 2016|accessdate=July 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn August 4, 2016, Westbrook agreed to a three-year extension to remain with the Thunder.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.todaysfastbreak.com/fastbreak-news/russell-westbrook-reportedly-working-toward-contract-extension/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=August 4, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160805190106/http://www.todaysfastbreak.com/fastbreak-news/russell-westbrook-reportedly-working-toward-contract-extension/ |archive-date=August 5, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\nWith an average of 31.6 points, 10.4 assists, and 10.7 rebounds, Westbrook became the first player since [[Oscar Robertson]] to average a triple-double for an entire NBA regular season, and only the second in NBA history (the other being Robertson). On April 2, 2017, Westbrook tied Oscar Robertson's record for most triple-doubles in an NBA season (41); he broke the record on April 9 against the [[Denver Nuggets]], marking his 42nd triple-double of the season. Westbrook, in that game, also hit the game winning buzzer beater from 36 feet, ending the Nuggets' playoffs hopes and securing the Thunder's 3rd seed matchup with the [[Houston Rockets]] in the NBA playoffs. Oklahoma City lost the playoff series in the first round to the Houston Rockets 4\u20131. Despite the team's loss, Westbrook averaged a +14 while on the court and a triple-double during the series and was named league MVP after the season.\n\n===2017\u20132019: Westbrook and George era===\n{{Main|2017\u201318 Oklahoma City Thunder season| 2018\u201319 Oklahoma City Thunder season}}\nIn the 2017 NBA draft, the Thunder selected guard [[Terrance Ferguson]] with the 21st pick, and signed him to a four-year rookie-scale contract.<ref>{{cite news|last=Belzer|first=Jason|title=2017 NBA Draft 1st Round Rookie Salary Projections|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jasonbelzer/2017/06/23/2017-nba-draft-1st-round-rookie-salary-projections/|magazine=[[Forbes]]|date=June 23, 2017|access-date=July 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\nTo further bolster the roster and improve Westbrook's supporting cast, the Thunder's front office made a series of aggressive moves to reshape the team. On July 6, 2017, the Thunder acquired four-time All-Star forward [[Paul George]] in a trade with the [[Indiana Pacers]] in exchange for guard [[Victor Oladipo]] and forward [[Domantas Sabonis]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Thunder Acquires All-Star Forward Paul George|url=http://www.nba.com/thunder/news/george-170706|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=July 6, 2017|accessdate=July 6, 2017}}</ref> The team then signed veteran point guard [[Raymond Felton]] and sharp-shooting power forward [[Patrick Patterson (basketball)|Patrick Patterson]] in free agency on July 10.<ref>{{cite news|title=Thunder Signs Raymond Felton|url=http://www.nba.com/thunder/news/raymond-felton-170710|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=July 10, 2017|accessdate=July 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Thunder Signs Patrick Patterson|url=http://www.nba.com/thunder/news/patrick-patterson-170710|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=July 10, 2017|accessdate=April 21, 2018}}</ref> Finally, on September 25, the Thunder acquired ten-time All-Star forward [[Carmelo Anthony]] from the [[New York Knicks]] in exchange for center [[Enes Kanter]], forward [[Doug McDermott]], and a 2018 second round draft pick they had previously acquired from the [[Chicago Bulls]] in the [[Cameron Payne]] trade.<ref>{{cite news|title=Thunder Acquires All-Star Forward Carmelo Anthony|url=http://www.nba.com/thunder/news/carmelo-anthony-170925|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|access-date=September 25, 2017|date=September 25, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Bulls acquire Payne, Morrow, and Lauvergne from Thunder|url=http://www.nba.com/bulls/news/bulls-acquire-payne-morrow-and-lauvergne-thunder|website=Bulls.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=February 23, 2017|accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref> On September 29, 2017, the Thunder signed [[Russell Westbrook]] to a five-year extension.<ref>{{cite news|last=Brunt|first=Cliff|title=Russell Westbrook decides he is all-in with Oklahoma City Thunder, signs five-year extension|url=http://www.nba.com/article/2017/09/29/report-russell-westbrook-accepts-five-year-extension-oklahoma-city-thunder|agency=Associated Press|website=NBA.com|date=September 27, 2017|access-date=October 28, 2018}}</ref> The Thunder finished the 2017\u201318 season with a 48\u201334 record and lost to the [[Utah Jazz]] 4\u20132 in the first round of the playoffs.\n\nIn the 2018 NBA draft, the Thunder selected guard [[Devon Hall]] with the 53rd pick and forward [[Kevin Hervey]] with the 57th pick.<ref>{{cite news|title=Thunder Selects Devon Hall and Kevin Hervey in 2018 NBA Draft|url=https://www.nba.com/thunder/news/draft-180621|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=June 21, 2018|access-date=October 28, 2018}}</ref> [[Devon Hall]] did not sign with the Thunder, instead signing with the [[Cairns Taipans]] of the Australian [[National Basketball League (Australia)|National Basketball League.]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Horne|first=Erik|title=Thunder second-rounder Devon Hall signs with Australia's National Basketball League|url=https://newsok.com/article/5604469/thunder-second-rounder-devon-hall-signs-with-australias-national-basketball-league|newspaper=[[The Oklahoman]]|date=August 11, 2018|access-date=October 28, 2018}}</ref> [[Kevin Hervey]] signed with the Thunder's [[NBA G League|NBA G-League]] affiliate, [[Oklahoma City Blue]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Afseth|first=Grant|title=Thunder draft pick Kevin Hervey will play this season for the OKC Blue|url=https://okcthunderwire.usatoday.com/2018/10/05/oklahoma-city-thunder-draft-pick-kevin-hervey-okc-blue-g-league/|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=October 5, 2018|access-date=October 28, 2018}}</ref> Additionally, the Thunder traded a 2019 second-round pick to acquire [[Hamidou Diallo]], who had been selected by the [[Brooklyn Nets]] with the 45th pick.<ref>{{cite news|title=Thunder Acquires Hamidou Diallo|url=https://www.nba.com/thunder/news/diallo-180706|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=July 6, 2018|access-date=October 28, 2018}}</ref> Diallo signed a three-year contract with the Thunder.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dang|first=Kenny|title=Thunder signed rookie Hamidou Diallo to a three year/$4M deal|url=https://www.welcometoloudcity.com/2018/7/26/17617378/thunder-rookie-hamidou-diallo-contract|website=WelcomeToLoudCity.com|publisher=[[SB Nation]]|date=July 26, 2018|access-date=October 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn July 6, 2018, [[Paul George]] re-signed with the Thunder.<ref>{{cite news|title=Thunder Signs Paul George to Multi-Year Contract|url=https://www.nba.com/thunder/news/george-180706|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=July 6, 2018|accessdate=August 31, 2018}}</ref> In July 2018, the Thunder traded forward [[Carmelo Anthony]] and a 2022 protected first round pick to the [[Atlanta Hawks]] in a three-way trade. In the trade, the Thunder acquired guard [[Dennis Schr\u00f6der|Dennis Schroder]] from the [[Atlanta Hawks]] and forward [[Timoth\u00e9 Luwawu-Cabarrot|Timothe Luwawu-Cabarrot]] from the [[Philadelphia 76ers]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Wojnarowski|first=Adrian|title=Sources: Melo headed to Hawks, will be waived|url=http://www.espn.com.au/nba/story/_/id/24141942/oklahoma-city-thunder-trade-carmelo-anthony-atlanta-hawks-dennis-schroder-mike-muscala|publisher=ESPN|date=July 20, 2018|access-date=October 28, 2018}}</ref> The Thunder also acquired guard [[Deonte Burton (basketball, born 1994)|Deonte Burton]], signing him to a [[two-way contract]] with the [[Oklahoma City Blue]].<ref>{{cite tweet|user=KeithSmithNBA|author=Keith Smith|number=1015652897910976513|date=July 7, 2018|title=The Oklahoma City Thunder have signed guard Deonte Burton to a two-way contract.}}</ref> Additionally, the Thunder acquired center [[Nerlens Noel]] in free agency,<ref>{{cite web|last=Wells|first=Adam|title=Nerlens Noel Reportedly Agrees to Contract with Thunder in Free Agency|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2755755-nerlens-noel-reportedly-agrees-to-contract-with-thunder-in-free-agency|website=[[Bleacher Report]]|date=July 3, 2018|access-date=October 28, 2018}}</ref> and traded for [[Abdel Nader]] from the [[Boston Celtics]].<ref>{{cite news|title=NBA notebook: OKC gets forward Abdel Nader from Celtics for guard Rodney Purvis|url=https://newsok.com/article/5602355/nowitzki-re-signs-with-mavericks-for-record-21st-season|newspaper=[[The Oklahoman]]|date=July 23, 2018|access-date=October 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2019\u2013present: Post-Westbrook Thunder Era Rebuilding===\nGeneral manager [[Sam Presti]] traded [[Paul George]] to the [[Los Angeles Clippers]] on July 10, 2019. In return, they received [[Danilo Gallinari]], [[Shai Gilgeous-Alexander]], and a record collection of future first-round draft picks. It was reported after the trade was announced that George had privately requested the trade to the Clippers as a result of superstar free agent [[Kawhi Leonard]] convincing George to team up with him on the Clippers.<ref>https://www.nba.com/clippers/clippers-acquire-six-time-nba-all-star-paul-george {{verify source |date=August 2019 |reason=This ref was deleted ([[Special:Diff/906027437]]) by a bug in VisualEditor and later restored by a bot from the original cite at [[Special:Permalink/906022480]] cite #62 - please verify the cite's accuracy and remove this {verify source} template. [[User:GreenC bot/Job 18]]}}</ref> They also traded forward [[Jerami Grant]] to the [[Denver Nuggets]] for a 2020 protected first-round pick.\n\nAfter the George trade, general manager Presti sensed that the future of the franchise was in jeopardy as the team could not seriously contend with Westbrook as the lone star. On July 16, the Thunder traded Westbrook to the Houston Rockets. In exchange, the Thunder received [[Chris Paul]], two future first-round draft picks, and the rights to two future pick swaps with the Rockets.<ref>{{cite news|title=Oklahoma City Acquires Chris Paul, Two First-Round Draft Picks and the Right to Two Swap Picks|url=https://www.nba.com/thunder/news/transaction-190716|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|website=OKCThunder.com|date=July 16, 2019|access-date=July 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Season-by-season record==\n''List of the last five seasons completed by the Thunder. For the full season-by-season history, see [[List of Oklahoma City Thunder seasons]].''\n\n'''''Note:''' GP = Games played, W = Wins, L = Losses, % = Winning Percentage'';\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"font-weight:bold; {{NBA color cell|Oklahoma City Thunder}};\"\n| Season || GP || W || L || W\u2013L% || Finish || Playoffs\n|-\n| [[2014\u201315 NBA season|2014\u201315]] || 82 || 45 || 37 || {{Winning percentage|45|37}} || 2nd, Northwest || Did not qualify\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n| [[2015\u201316 NBA season|2015\u201316]] || 82 || 55 || 27 || {{Winning percentage|55|27}} || 1st, Northwest || Lost in Conference Finals, 3\u20134 ([[Golden State Warriors|Warriors]])\n|-\n| [[2016\u201317 NBA season|2016\u201317]] || 82 || 47 || 35 || {{Winning percentage|47|35}} || 2nd, Northwest || Lost in First Round, 1\u20134 ([[Houston Rockets|Rockets]])\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n| 