0 Denotes Division championship\n|}\n\n==Home arenas==\n<!-- Do not remove arenas from Seattle. The Oklahoma City team is keeping the franchise history of the SuperSonics. Please see the talk page for link to settlement. -->\n''Note: All arenas used before 2008 were used by the defunct Seattle SuperSonics franchise.''\n\nSeattle arenas had hosted two [[NBA All-Star Game]]s; the [[1974 NBA All-Star Game|1974]] game in [[Seattle Center Coliseum]] and the [[1987 NBA All-Star Game|1987]] game in the [[Kingdome]], where SuperSonics forward [[Tom Chambers (basketball)|Tom Chambers]] grabbed [[NBA All-Star Game Most Valuable Player Award|MVP]] honors.\n*'''[[Seattle Center Coliseum]]''' 1967\u20131978 (occasionally used during the Kingdome years when the latter was unavailable due to either [[Seattle Mariners|Mariners]] or [[Seattle Seahawks|Seahawks]] games)\n*'''[[Kingdome]]''' 1978\u20131985\n*'''Seattle Center Coliseum''' 1985\u20131994\n*'''[[Tacoma Dome]]''' 1994\u20131995 (During Seattle Center Coliseum renovation)\n*'''[[KeyArena]]''' (the remodeled and renamed Seattle Center Coliseum) 1995\u20132008\n\n===Chesapeake Energy Arena (2008\u2013present)===\n{{main|Chesapeake Energy Arena}}\nOpened on June 8, 2002, as the Ford Center, Chesapeake Energy Arena was built without luxury accommodations but designed to accommodate luxury \"buildouts\" should a professional sports franchise make the Chesapeake Energy Arena their home arena. It was finished at a cost of $89.2 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chesapeakearena.com/about-the-arena/overview|title=Overview {{!}} Chesapeake Energy Arena|last=Arena|first=Chesapeake Energy|website=www.chesapeakearena.com|access-date=December 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nA plan for such build-out improvements began in 2007. It came in the wake of the acquisition of the Seattle SuperSonics by [[Professional Basketball Club LLC|an Oklahoma City-based ownership group]] the previous October. A city ballot initiative approved by a 62 percent margin on March 4, 2008, extended a prior one-cent city sales tax for a period of 15 months in order to fund $101 million in budgeted improvements to the arena and a separate $20 million practice facility for a relocated franchise.<ref name=knapp1>{{cite web |url=http://okc.about.com/od/politicalparties/a/fordcentervote.htm |title=Ford Center Arena Improvement Plan |last=Knapp |first=Adam |accessdate=November 17, 2010 |publisher=[[About.com]]}}</ref>\n\nRenovation work on the arena was delayed by a sales tax-receipts shortfall during the 2008\u201310 economic crisis.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.okc.gov/agendapub/cache/2/xo5hufii3c1njdqg3sqfuw55/98900111172010122518933.PDF |title=MAPS 3 Citizens Advisory Board Presentation |date=August 24, 2010 |work=City of Oklahoma City |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160411001503/http://www.okc.gov/agendapub/cache/2/xo5hufii3c1njdqg3sqfuw55/98900111172010122518933.PDF |archivedate=April 11, 2016 }}</ref> Revised plans limited the size of a new glass entryway and eliminated a practice court to accommodate the shortfall.<ref>{{cite web |last=Rohde |first=John |title=Ford Center practice gym eliminated from renovations |url=http://www.newsok.com/article/3483508 |work=The Oklahoman |date=August 8, 2010 |accessdate=November 17, 2010}}</ref> Major construction work on the arena expansion was also delayed from the summer of 2010 to the summer of 2011. Seating capacity of the stadium is 18,203 for professional NBA basketball games.\n\nSimilar revisions were made to the plans for the Thunder's separate practice facility, for a total cost savings of approximately $14 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newsok.com/article/3474044 |title=Oklahoma City might save as much as $14 million on Ford Center renovations, practice facility |work=The Oklahoman |date=July 7, 2010 |accessdate=November 17, 2010}}</ref> The Thunder's practice facility completion date was pushed back to approximately March 2011.<ref>{{cite web |last=Rohde |first=John |title=Thunder practice facility set for March completion |url=http://newsok.com/thunder-practice-facility-set-for-march-completion/article/3515264 |work=The Oklahoman|date=November 16, 2010 |accessdate=November 17, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Mascots==\n<!-- Do not remove mascots from Seattle. Please see the talk page for link to settlement. -->\n''Note: All mascots used before 2008 were used by the defunct Seattle SuperSonics franchise.''\n*[[Wheedle]], 1978\u20131985\n*[[Squatch]], 1993\u20132008\n\n===Rumble the Bison===\n{{main|Rumble the Bison}}\nOn February 17, 2009, Rumble the Bison was introduced as the new Oklahoma City Thunder mascot during halftime of a game against the [[2008\u201309 New Orleans Hornets season|New Orleans Hornets]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Rumble the Bison Debuts as Thunder Mascot|url=http://www.nba.com/thunder/news/rumbledebuts_090217.html|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=February 17, 2009|accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref> Rumble was the winner of the 2008\u20132009 NBA Mascot of the Year.<ref name=\"award\">{{cite press release|title=Rumble the Bison Named NBA Mascot of the Year|url=http://www.nba.com/thunder/news/release_090813.html|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=August 13, 2009|accessdate=August 26, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Fanbase==\nDuring the [[2012 NBA Finals]], sportswriter [[Bill Simmons]] published a piece on the team's fan base in his [[ESPN]]-sponsored Web outlet, ''[[Grantland|Grantland.com]]'', in which he noted the unusual enthusiasm of the city for its team:\n{{cquote|With the possible exception of [[Portland Trail Blazers|Portland]], no NBA team means more to its city. This goes beyond having the loudest fans. There's genuine devotion here. These people arrived a good 45 minutes early for last night's Game 1&nbsp;\u2014 and by \"these people\" I mean \"everyone with a ticket\"&nbsp;\u2014 then clapped their way through pregame warm-ups with such infectious enthusiasm that I remember saying to a friend, \"No way these yahoos keep this up for three hours, they're going to burn out.\" Wrong. You know what burned out? My eardrums. My head is still ringing.<ref name=Simmons>{{cite web|last=Simmons|first=Bill|authorlink=Bill Simmons|title=Thunder Family Values|url=http://www.grantland.com/story/_/id/8047976/thunder-family-values|work=[[Grantland|Grantland.com]]|date=June 13, 2012|accessdate=June 4, 2013}}</ref>}}\n\nSimmons speculated that the [[Oklahoma City bombing]] played a major part in the team's culture, noting that Thunder general manager [[Sam Presti]] has every new Thunder player visit the [[Oklahoma City National Memorial]], and encourages players to look into the stands and consider that many of the team's fans were personally affected by the event. He also noted, however, that the fact that the Thunder is the only team from Oklahoma City (or indeed the state of Oklahoma) in one of the nation's four major leagues contributes mightily to the city's devotion.<ref name=Simmons/>\n\nThunder fans are also reportedly much more likely to attend major home games than most other NBA fanbases. According to a source in the ticket industry, only five percent of tickets to the 2012 NBA conference finals listed for sale on secondary market sites such as [[StubHub]] were for Thunder home games, and for every ticket listed for a Thunder home game in the 2012 NBA Finals, 10 tickets for Heat home games were listed.<ref name=Simmons/>\n\nThe team and its fanbase regularly use the slogan \"Thunder Up!\" which was prominently displayed on T-shirts during the 2012 playoffs.\n\n==Players==\n===Current roster===\n{{Oklahoma City Thunder roster}}\n<!-- Do not place the depth chart in this article, since it constitutes point of view and original research -->\n\n===Former players===\n:''For the complete list of players see: [[Seattle SuperSonics all-time roster]] / [[Oklahoma City Thunder all-time roster]]''\n\n===Retained draft rights===\nThe Thunder holds the draft rights to the following unsigned draft picks who have been playing outside the NBA. A drafted player, either an international draftee or a college draftee who is not signed by the team that drafted him, is allowed to sign with any non-NBA teams. In this case, the team retains the player's draft rights in the NBA until one year after the player's contract with the non-NBA team ends.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbafaq.com/salarycap.htm|title=NBA Salary Cap FAQ \u2013 2011 Collective Bargaining Agreement|quote=If the player is already under contract to, or signs a contract with a non-NBA team, the team retains the player's draft rights for one year after the player's obligation to the non-NBA team ends. Essentially, the clock stops as long as the player plays pro ball outside the NBA.|first=Larry|last=Coon|authorlink=Larry Coon|accessdate=April 13, 2014}}</ref> This list includes draft rights that were acquired from trades with other teams.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:left; font-size:90%;\"\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell|Oklahoma City Thunder}};\"|Draft\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell|Oklahoma City Thunder}};\"|Round\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell|Oklahoma City Thunder}};\"|Pick\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell|Oklahoma City Thunder}};\"|Player\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell|Oklahoma City Thunder}};\"|Pos.\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell|Oklahoma City Thunder}};\"|Nationality\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell|Oklahoma City Thunder}};\"|Current team\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell|Oklahoma City Thunder}};\"|Note(s)\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"{{NBA color cell|Oklahoma City Thunder}};\"|Ref\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[2003 NBA draft|2003]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|34\n| {{sortname|Sofoklis|Schortsanitis}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|C\n| {{flagu|Greece}}\n| [[Ionikos Nikaias B.C.|Ionikos Nikaias]] ([[Greek Basket League|Greece]])\n| Acquired from the [[Los Angeles Clippers]] (via [[Atlanta Hawks|Atlanta]])\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite news|title=Thunder Acquires Schortsanitis and Trade Exception|url=http://www.nba.com/thunder/release_schortsanitis_140715|date=July 15, 2014|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|accessdate=February 4, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[2003 NBA draft|2003]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|35\n| {{sortname|Szymon|Szewczyk}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| F/C\n| {{flagu|Poland}} \n| [[KK W\u0142oc\u0142awek|Anwil W\u0142oc\u0142awek]] ([[Polish Basketball League|Poland]])\n| Acquired from the [[Milwaukee Bucks]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite news|title=Thunder Acquires Trade Exception|url=http://www.nba.com/thunder/news/release_tradeexception_130711|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=July 11, 2013|accessdate=April 21, 2014}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Individual awards===\nFor details on [[Seattle SuperSonics]] history, see ''[[Seattle SuperSonics#High points|Seattle SuperSonics records]]''.\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-break}}\n'''[[NBA Most Valuable Player Award|NBA Most Valuable Player]]'''\n*[[Kevin Durant]]&nbsp;\u2013 2014\n*[[Russell Westbrook]]&nbsp;\u2013 2017\n\n'''[[List of NBA All-Star Game head coaches|NBA All-Star head coach]]'''\n*[[Scott Brooks]]&nbsp;\u2013 2012, 2014\n\n'''[[NBA Coach of the Year Award|NBA Coach of the Year]]'''\n*[[Scott Brooks]]&nbsp;\u2013 2010\n\n'''[[NBA Sixth Man of the Year Award|NBA Sixth Man of the Year]]'''\n*[[James Harden]]&nbsp;\u2013 2012\n\n'''[[NBA Community Assist Award]]'''\n*[[Russell Westbrook]]&nbsp;\u2013 2015\n\n'''[[NBA scoring champion]]'''\n*[[Kevin Durant]]&nbsp;\u2013 2010\u20132012, 2014\n*[[Russell Westbrook]]&nbsp;\u2013 2015, 2017\n\n'''[[All-NBA First Team]]'''\n*[[Kevin Durant]]&nbsp;\u2013 2010\u20132014\n*[[Russell Westbrook]] &nbsp;\u2013 2016, 2017\n*[[Paul George]]&nbsp;\u2013 2019\n\n'''[[All-NBA Second Team]]'''\n*[[Russell Westbrook]]&nbsp;\u2013 2011\u20132013, 2015, 2018\n*[[Kevin Durant]]&nbsp;\u2013 2016\n\n'''[[All-NBA Third Team]]'''\n*[[Paul George]]&nbsp;\u2013 2018\n*[[Russell Westbrook]] &nbsp;\u2013 2019\n\n'''[[NBA All-Defensive First Team]]'''\n*[[Serge Ibaka]]&nbsp;\u2013 2012\u20132014\n*[[Paul George]] &nbsp;\u2013 2019\n\n{{Col-break}}\n'''[[NBA All-Defensive Second Team]]'''\n*[[Thabo Sefolosha]]&nbsp;\u2013 2010\n*[[Andre Roberson]]&nbsp;\u2013 2017\n\n'''[[NBA All-Rookie First Team]]'''\n*[[Russell Westbrook]]&nbsp;\u2013 2009\n\n'''[[NBA All-Rookie Second Team]]'''\n*[[James Harden]]&nbsp;\u2013 2010\n*[[Steven Adams]]&nbsp;- 2014\n\n'''[[NBA All-Star Game]]'''\n*[[Kevin Durant]]&nbsp;\u2013 2010\u20132016\n*[[Russell Westbrook]]&nbsp;\u2013 2011\u20132013, 2015\u20132019\n*[[Paul George]]&nbsp;\u2013 2018, 2019\n*[[Chris Paul]]&nbsp;\u2013 2020\n{{col-end}}\n\n'''[[NBA All Star Game|NBA All Star Game Most Valuable Player]]'''\n*[[Kevin Durant]]&nbsp;\u2013 2012\n*[[Russell Westbrook]]&nbsp; \u2013 2015, 2016\n\n===Retired numbers===\nSince relocating from Seattle to Oklahoma City, the Thunder has officially retired one jersey number. On March 20, 2019, the club officially retired number 4 in honor of [[Nick Collison]], who played for the team from 2003\u20132018.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Thunder Set to Retire Nick Collison's No. 4|url=https://www.nba.com/thunder/news/collison-190112|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|website=OKCThunder.com|date=January 12, 2019|access-date=November 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs the Thunder's original iteration, the Seattle SuperSonics had retired six numbers. In addition, the SuperSonics awarded an honorary [[microphone]] to longtime broadcaster [[Bob Blackburn (announcer)|Bob Blackburn]], who had called the majority of the team's games from 1967 through 1992.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hanging From the Rafters|url=http://www.nba.com/history/retired_numbers.html|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=August 9, 2015|accessdate=August 9, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Raley|first=Dan|title=Where Are They Now? Blackburn gave Sonics a voice|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/news/article/Where-Are-They-Now-Blackburn-gave-Sonics-a-voice-1195822.php|newspaper=Seattle Post-Intelligencer|date=February 14, 2006|accessdate=August 9, 2015}}</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"{{NBA color cell|Oklahoma City Thunder}};\"|'''Oklahoma City Thunder retired numbers'''\n|-\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell2|Oklahoma City Thunder}};\"|No.\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell2|Oklahoma City Thunder}};\"|Player\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell2|Oklahoma City Thunder}};\"|Position\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell2|Oklahoma City Thunder}};\"|Tenure\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell2|Oklahoma City Thunder}};\"|Date\n|-\n| '''1''' || [[Gus Williams (basketball)|Gus Williams]] || G || 1977\u20131984 || March 26, 2004\n|-\n| '''4''' || [[Nick Collison]] || F || 2003\u20132018 || March 20, 2019\n|-\n| '''10''' || [[Nate McMillan]] || G || 1986\u20131998 <sup>1</sup> || March 24, 1999\n|-\n| '''19''' || [[Lenny Wilkens]] || G || 1968\u20131972 <sup>2</sup> || October 19, 1979\n|-\n| '''24''' || [[Spencer Haywood]] || F || 1970\u20131975 || February 26, 2007\n|-\n| '''32''' || [[Fred Brown (basketball)|Fred Brown]] || G || 1971\u20131984 || November 6, 1986\n|-\n| '''43''' || [[Jack Sikma]] || C || 1977\u20131986 || November 21, 1992\n|-\n| [[File:Exquisite-microphone.png|40px]] || [[Bob Blackburn (announcer)|Bob Blackburn]] || Broadcaster || 1967\u20131992 || \n|}\n'''Notes:'''\n* <sup>1</sup> ''Served as head coach (2000\u20132005).''\n* <sup>2</sup> ''Served as head coach (1969\u20131972; 1977\u20131985).''\n\n==Staff==\n===Head coaches===\n{{Main|List of Oklahoma City Thunder head coaches}}\n\n===Executives===\nFor the complete list of [[Seattle SuperSonics]] executives, see: ''[[Seattle SuperSonics#General managers|Seattle SuperSonics executives]]''.\n\n*2008\u2013present: [[Sam Presti]]\n\n==Logos and uniforms==\nThe Oklahoma City Thunder unveiled their first logo on September 3, 2008. According to majority owner [[Clay Bennett (businessman)|Clay Bennett]], the team's logo takes several of its elements from other Oklahoma sports teams, such as the [[Oklahoma Sooners]] and [[Oklahoma State Cowboys and Cowgirls]].<ref name=\"nameannouncement\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Defining Moments: 10 Years of Thunder Basketball|url=https://www.nba.com/thunder/10/definingmoments|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=July 2, 2018|accessdate=December 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Baldwin|first=Mike|title=Sky blue will be the color|url=http://newsok.com/article/3292623|newspaper=The Oklahoman|date=September 4, 2008|accessdate=May 20, 2016}}</ref> The uniform design was unveiled on September 29, 2008.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Thunder Jerseys Available for Presale|url=http://www.nba.com/thunder/news/jerseys_080930.html|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=September 30, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091202095222/http://www.nba.com/thunder/news/jerseys_080930.html|archivedate=December 2, 2009|accessdate=May 20, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Baldwin|first=Mike|title=The uniform: Thunder players turn models|url=http://newsok.com/article/3304904|newspaper=The Oklahoman|date=September 30, 2008|accessdate=May 20, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Thunder 'flashes' new uniforms|url=http://www.news9.com/global/story.asp?s=9050815|publisher=[[KWTV-DT]]|date=September 22, 2008|accessdate=October 2, 2008}}</ref>\n\nAn alternate uniform was unveiled on November 8, 2012, featuring only navy blue and white colors. Unlike their regular uniforms, the wordmarks on the alternate are written vertically.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dwyer|first=Kelly|title=The Oklahoma City Thunder unveil alternate uniforms, to mild local acclaim|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nba-ball-dont-lie/oklahoma-city-thunder-unveil-alternate-uniforms-mild-local-152303049--nba.html|work=Yahoo! Sports|date=November 9, 2012|accessdate=November 10, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Thunder Alternate Uniform, November 9, 2012|url=http://www.nba.com/thunder/features/uniform_inspiration|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=November 9, 2012|accessdate=November 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\nA second alternate uniform was unveiled on March 1, 2015. A white uniform with sleeves, it features the Thunder partial logo in the center of the chest, and the shorts showcase bolts in light blue and sunset colors.<ref>{{cite press release|title=New Thunder Uniform Reflects Hometown Spirit|url=http://www.nba.com/thunder/news/release_pridejersey_150301|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=March 1, 2015|accessdate=March 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\nA third alternate uniform was unveiled on September 25, 2015. A sunset-colored uniform, it features the Oklahoma City abbreviation \"OKC\" in navy block letters trimmed in white. On the back of the jersey, player names sit below the numbers. The shorts display a sunset base with navy panels down the side showcasing the Thunder partial logo on each leg. The Thunder wore the sunset alternates for 18 games in the 2015\u20132016 season, including all 13 of its Sunday games.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Thunder Unveils New Alternate Uniform for 2015-16|url=http://www.nba.com/thunder/news/release_sunset_uniforms_150925|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=September 25, 2015|accessdate=September 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMoving to [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] in 2017, the Thunder kept their existing white (\"Association\") and blue (\"Icon\") uniforms almost intact with the exception of the \"OKC\" abbreviation on the beltline and truncated shoulder stripes.<ref>{{cite press release|title=New Technology Helps Nike Build Thunder Uniforms|url=https://www.nba.com/thunder/news/nike-uniforms-170726|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=July 27, 2017|accessdate=December 26, 2018}}</ref> The team also released a new alternate \"Statement\" uniform with an italicized \"OKC\" lettering in sunset orange and a navy base with blue gradients that evoke sound waves generated from the team's fan base.<ref>{{cite press release|title=New Thunder Alternate Uniform Makes a Statement|url=https://www.nba.com/thunder/news/statement-uniform-170915|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=September 15, 2017|accessdate=December 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Thunder also collaborated with Nike to produce annual \"City\" edition uniforms that intend to pay tribute to local cultures or team traditions. The 2017\u201318 \"City\" uniform featured a grey base with sunset orange and blue lines that were inspired by the Thunder's uptempo style.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Nike NBA City Edition Uniform|url=https://news.nike.com/news/nike-nba-city-edition-uniform|website=Nike.com|publisher=Nike, Inc.|date=December 27, 2017|accessdate=December 26, 2018}}</ref> For 2018\u201319, the Thunder's \"City\" uniform featured a turquoise base and bold white lettering with navy and sunset orange trim; the uniform was inspired by Oklahoma's Native American heritage.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Thunder Unveils New Turquoise Uniform Honoring Oklahoma's Native American Heritage|url=https://www.nba.com/thunder/corporate-news/native-heritage-uniforms-181101|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=November 1, 2018|access-date=December 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nNike also released an \"Earned\" uniform starting with the 2018\u201319 season and were only given to the 16 teams who qualified in the [[2018 NBA Playoffs]]. The Thunder's \"Earned\" uniform was a basic palette swap of the team's \"Statement\" uniforms, featuring a sunset orange base and navy letters.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Teams unveil Earned Edition uniforms for 2018-19 season|url=http://www.nba.com/article/2018/12/12/nba-unveils-earned-edition-uniforms|website=NBA.com|date=December 12, 2018|accessdate=December 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBeginning with the 2019\u201320 season, the Thunder unveiled new uniforms. The white \"Association\" uniform now featured the city name in front along with the outline of the state of Oklahoma on the beltline. The front of the blue \"Icon\" uniform now reads the team name in front while keeping the OKC acronym on the beltline. Their sunset orange \"Earned\" uniforms from the previous season became the basis of their new \"Statement\" uniform, albeit with lighter blue lettering. A new \"City\" uniform for the season commemorated the 25th anniversary of the [[Oklahoma City bombing]] and it featured a black and gold palette.<ref name=\"OKCThunderUnis2019\" />\n\n==Television and radio==\n===Radio===\n{{Main|Thunder Radio Network}}\n\nAll Thunder games are broadcast on the [[Thunder Radio Network]], fronted by flagship stations [[WWLS-FM]] 98.1 and [[KWPN (AM)|KWPN]] AM 640 in Oklahoma City. [[Matt Pinto]] is the radio voice of the Thunder.<ref>{{cite news|title=Thunder Radio Network|url=http://www.nba.com/thunder/news/thunder_radio_network|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=March 7, 2015|accessdate=March 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Television===\nFor their first two seasons, the Thunder's TV broadcasts were split between [[Fox Sports Oklahoma]] (a regional fork of [[Fox Sports Southwest]]), which broadcast most of the games, and independent station [[KSBI]] (channel 52), with around 65 Thunder games airing during the season and more than half of the games available in HD on Fox Sports Oklahoma, along with other team-related programming such as pre-game shows. Around 15 to 20 regular-season games were broadcast over the air on KSBI, which had a network of re-broadcasters spanning the entire state. All televised games are called by [[Brian Davis (sportscaster)|Brian Davis]] on play-by-play and [[Michael Cage]] as color commentator.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bracht|first=Mel|title=FS Oklahoma to air Thunder games|url=http://newsok.com/fs-oklahoma-to-air-thunder-games/article/3304544/?tm=1222733614|newspaper=The Oklahoman|date=September 29, 2008|accessdate=September 29, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Bracht|first=Mel|title=KSBI to air Thunder games|url=http://newsok.com/ksbi-to-air-thunder-games/article/3306605|newspaper=The Oklahoman|date=October 3, 2008|accessdate=December 20, 2018}}</ref> During the [[2009\u201310 NBA season|2009\u201310 season]], KSBI telecast all Thunder games it aired in high definition (KSBI had previously aired in HD the first regular-season game played at the Ford Center&nbsp;\u2013 against the Milwaukee Bucks on October 29, 2008&nbsp;\u2013 while all other games during the [[2008\u201309 NBA season|2008\u201309 season]] were telecast on KSBI in standard definition).\n\nOn August 3, 2010, the Thunder signed a new exclusive multi-year agreement with Fox Sports Oklahoma, beginning with the [[2010\u201311 NBA season|2010\u201311 season]], ending the team's broadcasts on KSBI.<ref>{{cite news|title=Thunder Signs Exclusive Television Agreement with FOX Sports Southwest|url=http://www.nba.com/thunder/news/thunder_signs_tvFXSW_100803.html|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=August 3, 2010|accessdate=January 25, 2015}}</ref> On October 22, 2012, the Thunder announced that Lesley McCaslin would be the new Thunder sideline reporter.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bracht|first=Mel|title=OKC Thunder: Lesley McCaslin named team's courtside reporter|url=http://newsok.com/lesley-mccaslin-named-okc-thunders-courtside-reporter/article/3721328|newspaper=The Oklahoman|date=October 22, 2012|accessdate=October 27, 2012}}</ref> On July 21, 2014, the Thunder announced that Long would not return to be its TV color commentator on Fox Sports Oklahoma.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mayberry|first=Darnell|title=Oklahoma City Thunder TV analyst Grant Long resigns from position|url=http://newsok.com/thunder-tv-analyst-grant-long-resigns-from-position/article/5011724|newspaper=The Oklahoman|date=July 21, 2014|accessdate=January 25, 2015}}</ref> On September 17, 2014, the Oklahoma City Thunder announced that 15-year NBA veteran Michael Cage would be the new color analyst, joining Brian Davis on television and Matt Pinto on the radio when the game is not on Fox Sports Oklahoma.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michael Cage to Join Thunder Broadcast Team|url=http://www.nba.com/thunder/news/release_cage_140917|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=September 17, 2014|accessdate=January 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDavis was replaced as the television play-by-play announcer by Chris Fisher prior to the 2018\u201319 season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chris Fisher Joins Thunder Broadcast Team on Fox Sports Oklahoma|url=https://www.nba.com/thunder/news/release-fisher-180924|website=OKCThunder.com|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|date=September 24, 2018|accessdate=December 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|group=upper-alpha}}\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Oklahoma City Thunder}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* [https://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/OKC/ Oklahoma City Thunder] at Basketball-Reference.com\n\n{{Oklahoma City Thunder}}\n{{Navboxes|titlestyle = {{NBA color cell|Oklahoma City Thunder|border=2}}|list =\n{{Oklahoma City Thunder seasons}}\n{{NBArelocated}}\n{{NBA}}\n{{Oklahoma Sports}}\n{{Oklahoma City}}\n}}\n{{Portal bar|Sports|Oklahoma}}\n\n[[Category:Oklahoma City Thunder| ]]\n[[Category:National Basketball Association teams]]\n[[Category:Seattle SuperSonics]]\n[[Category:Sports in Oklahoma City]]\n[[Category:Basketball teams established in 1967]]\n[[Category:Basketball teams established in 2008]]\n[[Category:2008 establishments in Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Relocated National Basketball Association teams]]\n[[Category:Basketball teams in Oklahoma]]\n", "name_user": "DBOOKISDAGOAT01", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changed dates", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.